<section xml:id="review-graphing-lines" permid="JtD">
  <title>Graphing Lines Chapter Review</title>
  <subsection permid="pAM">
    <title>Cartesian Coordinates</title>
    <p permid="Ehh">
      In <xref ref="section-cartesian-coordinates">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of the <xref ref="definition-cartesian-coordinate-system" text="title">Cartesian Coordinate System</xref>
      and how to plot points using the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>-axes.
    </p>
        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
            <p>The Cartesian coordinate system identifies the location of every point in a plane with an ordered pair. The first coordinate is the horizontal, <m>x</m>, distance and the second coordinate is the vertical, <m>y</m>, distance.</p>
        </paragraphs> -->
    <example permid="DEr">
      <statement>
        <p permid="oop">
          On paper, sketch a Cartesian coordinate system with units,
          and then plot the following points:
          <m>(3,2),(-5,-1),(0,-3),(4,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="VWq">
        <figure permid="qzb">
          <caption>A Cartesian grid with the four points plotted.</caption>
          <image permid="bEy">
            <description>a Cartesian grid with four points plotted; the point (3,2) is 3 units to the right of the origin and two units up; the point (-5,-1) is 5 units to the left of the origin and 1 unit down; the point (0,-3) is on the y-axis 3 units down; the point (4,0) is right 4 units along the x-axis.</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 2)} node[above] {$(3,2)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-5, -1)} node[below] {$(-5,-1)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, -3)} node[right] {$(0,-3)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4, 0)} node[above] {$(4,0)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="VHV">
    <title>Graphing Equations</title>
    <p permid="koq">
      In <xref ref="section-graphing-equations">Section</xref>
      we covered how to plot solutions to equations to produce a graph of the equation.
    </p>
            <!-- <p>To graph an equation with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we can choose some reasonable <m>x</m>-values, then calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot the <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs as points. For many (not-so-complicated) algebraic equations, connecting those points with a smooth curve will produce an excellent graph.</p> -->
    <example permid="jLA">
      <statement>
        <p permid="Uvy">
          Graph the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Cdz">
        <figure permid="iUC">
          <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
          <sidebyside margins="0%" permid="PSJ">

            <table permid="HLH">
              <caption>Set up the table</caption>
              <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor" permid="TZZ">
                <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                  <cell>Point</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="none">
                  <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </table>

            <table permid="nSQ">
              <caption>Complete the table</caption>
              <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor" permid="Ahi">
                <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                  <cell>Point</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="none">
                  <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </table>

          </sidebyside>

        </figure>

        <p permid="WGk">
          We use points from the table to graph the equation.
          First, plot each point carefully.
          Then, connect the points with a smooth curve.
          Here, the curve is a straight line.
          Lastly, we can communicate that the graph extends further by sketching arrows on both ends of the line.
        </p>

        <figure permid="PbL">
          <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="vZS">
            <figure permid="CrU">
              <caption>Use points from the table</caption>
              <image permid="gor">
                <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                xtick=,
                                minor xtick=,
                                ytick=,
                                minor ytick=,]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
              </image>

            </figure>

            <figure permid="viU">
              <caption>Connect the points in whatever pattern is apparent</caption>
              <image permid="MvA">
                <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1);they are connected with a solid line with arrows on each end</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                xtick=,
                                minor xtick=,
                                ytick=,
                                minor ytick=,]
                        \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
              </image>

            </figure>
          </sidebyside>

        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="BPe">
    <title>Exploring Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>
    <p permid="Qvz">
      In <xref ref="section-exploring-two-variable-data-and-rate-of-change">Section</xref>
      we covered how to find patterns in tables of data and how to calculate the <xref ref="definition-rate-of-change" text="title">rate of change</xref> between points in data.
    </p>

    <paragraphs permid="rpZ">
      <title>Exploring Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>
      <p permid="wCI">
        For a linear relationship, by its data in a table,
        we can see the rate of change (slope) and the line's <m>y</m>-intercept,
        thus writing the equation.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example permid="chb">
      <statement>
        <sidebyside permid="Iok">
          <p permid="ACH">
            Write an equation in the form
            <m>y=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.
          </p>

          <table permid="fiY">
            <caption>A table of linear data.</caption>
            <tabular permid="Lqh">
              <row bottom="medium">
                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>

          </table>

        </sidebyside>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="ikI">
        <sidebyside permid="ovt">
          <p permid="bqd">
            We consider how the values change from one row to the next.
            From row to row, the <m>x</m>-value increases by <m>1</m>.
            Also, the <m>y</m>-value decreases by <m>2</m> from row to row.
          </p>

          <tabular  permid="idE">
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell />
            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            <cell />
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell />
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
            <cell />
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
          </row>
          </tabular>

        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="Hxm">
          Since row-to-row change is always <m>1</m> for <m>x</m> and is always <m>-2</m> for <m>y</m>,
          the rate of change from one row to another row is always the same:
          <m>-2</m> units of <m>y</m> for every <m>1</m> unit of <m>x</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="nEv">
          We know that the output for <m>x = 0</m> is <m>y = -4</m>.
          And our observation about the constant rate of change tells us that if we increase the input by <m>x</m> units from <m>0</m>,
          the output should decrease by
          <m>\overbrace{(-2)+(-2)+\cdots+(-2)}^{x\text{ times}}</m>,
          which is <m>-2x</m>.
          So the output would be <m>-4-2x</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="TLE">
          So the equation is <m>y=-2x-4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="hWn">
    <title>Slope</title>
    <idx><h>slope</h><h>review</h></idx>

    <p permid="cJR">
      In <xref ref="section-slope">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-slope" text="title">slope</xref>
      and how to use slope-triangles to calculate slope.
      There is also the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref>
      which helps find the slope through any two points.
    </p>
            <!-- <p>When <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between any two points is always the same, we call this common rate of change the <term>slope</term>. Since having a constant rate of change means the graph will be a straight line, it's also called the <term>slope of the line</term>.</p>

            <p>We can find a line's slope by drawing a slope-triangle on the line's graph, and then using the formula<men>m=\frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</men></p> -->
    <example permid="UCC">
      <statement>
        <p permid="gJQ">
          Find the slope of the line in the following graph.
        </p>

        <figure permid="MQZ">
          <caption>The line with two points indicated.</caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="sCJ">
            <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27).</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={x},
                            ylabel={y},
                            xmin=-2,xmax=8,
                            ymin=-5,ymax=30,
                            minor ytick=,
                            minor xtick=,
                            xtick={2,4,6},
                            ytick={5,10,...,25},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot+[domain = -2:6.75]{4*x+3};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="OrR">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="gQU">
          <figure permid="fZW">
            <caption>The line with a slope triangle drawn.</caption>
            <image permid="YJS">
              <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12".</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={x},
                            ylabel={y},
                            xmin=-2,xmax=8,
                            ymin=-5,ymax=30,
                            minor ytick=,
                            minor xtick=,
                            xtick={2,4,6},
                            ytick={5,10,...,25},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot+[domain = -2:6.75]{4*x+3};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

          <p permid="zSN">
            We picked two points on the line,
            and then drew a slope triangle.
            Next, we will do:
            <me permid="FWu">
              \text{slope}=\frac{12}{3}=4
            </me>
            The line's slope is <m>4</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="AJL">
      <title>Finding a Line's Slope by the Slope Formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p permid="sYi">
          Use the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref>
          to find the slope of the line that passes through the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and <m>(4,-2)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="uza">
        <p permid="Mhf">
          <md permid="mdD">
            <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-(25)}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
          </md>
          The line's slope is <m>-3</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="Odw">
    <title>Slope-Intercept Form</title>
    <p permid="IRa">
      In <xref ref="section-slope-intercept-form">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope intercept-form</xref>
      and both wrote equations in slope-intercept form and graphed lines given in slope-intercept form.
    </p>
        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Graphing a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</title>
            <p>A line's equation in slope-intercept form looks like <m>y=mx+b</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>b</m> is the <m>y</m> value of the line's <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>
            <p>We can use a line's <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles to graph it.</p>
        </paragraphs> -->
    <example permid="MYd">
      <statement>
        <p permid="Zfr">
          Graph the line <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="aGj">
        <figure permid="soo">
          <caption>Graphing <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4</m></caption>
          <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%" permid="Zmv">
            <figure permid="izd">
              <caption>First, plot the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>(0,4)</m>.</caption>
              <image permid="ERb">
                <description>a Cartesian grid with the point (0,4) plotted</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                ]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)} node[above right] {$(0,4)$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
              </image>

            </figure>

            <figure permid="Yvx">
              <caption>The slope is <m>-\frac{5}{2}=\frac{-5}{2}=\frac{5}{-2}</m>. So we can try using a <q>run</q> of <m>2</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>-5</m> or a <q>run</q> of <m>-2</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>5</m>.</caption>
              <image permid="kYk">
                <description>the previous plot of the y-intercept with slope triangles drawn; they go right 2 and down 5 twice to the right; from the y-intercept they also go up 5 and left 2 once; the points plotted are (-2,9), (0,4), (2,-1), (4,-6)</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                ]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (2,4) (2,-1)};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(2,-1) (4,-1) (4,-6)};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (-2,4) (-2,9)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[below left] {$(2,-9)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[below left] {$(2,-1)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-6)} node[above right] {$(4,-6)$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
              </image>

            </figure>

            <figure permid="ECG">
              <caption>Arrowheads and labels are encouraged.</caption>
              <image permid="Rft">
                <description>the previous plot with a solid line drawn through all of the points; there are arrowheads on each end of the line</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-2.4:5.6] {-5/2*x+4} node[pos=0.6,sloped,above] {$y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-6)};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
              </image>

            </figure>
          </sidebyside>

        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <paragraphs permid="Xxi">
      <title>Writing a Line's Equation in Slope-Intercept Form Based on Graph</title>
      <p permid="oYj">
        Given a line's graph, we can identify its <m>y</m>-intercept,
        and then find its slope by a slope triangle.
        With a line's slope and <m>y</m>-intercept,
        we can write its equation in the form of <m>y=mx+b</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example permid="tfm">
      <statement>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="FtE">
          <p permid="FmA">
            Find the equation of the line in the graph.
          </p>

          <figure permid="ltJ">
            <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
            <image permid="xmC">
              <description>a coordinate graph of a line;three points on the line are (-3,12),(0,10) and (3,8)</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=16,
                                ytick={2,4,...,14},
                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,16},
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="GNs">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="lAN">
          <figure permid="QQY">
            <caption>Identify the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>10</m>.</caption>
            <image permid="dtL">
              <description>the previous graph showing the line crosses the y-axis at 10 or (0,10)</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=16,
                                ytick={2,4,...,14},
                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,16},
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)} node[right] {$(0,10)$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

          <figure permid="wYh">
            <caption>Identify the line's slope by a slope triangle. Note that we can pick any two points on the line to create a slope triangle. We would get the same slope: <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m></caption>
            <image permid="JAU">
              <description>the previous graph with slope triangles drawn moving right 3 units and down two units</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                ytick={0,5,15,20},
                                y axis line style = {->},
                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8)} node[below] {$(3,8)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,12)} node[above] {$(-3,12)$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,10) (3,10)} node[pos=0.5,above,align=center] {$3$};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,10) (3,8)} node[pos=0.5,right,align=center] {$-2$};
                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,10) (0,10)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=center] {$3$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-3,10) (-3,12)} node[pos=0.5,left,align=center] {$-2$};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="kJP">
          With the line's slope <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept <m>10</m>,
          we can write the line's equation in slope-intercept form:
          <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="ukF">
    <title>Point-Slope Form</title>
    <p permid="Vfs">
      In <xref ref="section-point-slope-form">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-point-slope-form" text="title">point-slope form</xref>
      and both wrote equations in point-slope form and graphed lines given in point-slope form.
    </p>
            <!-- <p>A line's point-slope form equation is in the form of <m>y=m\left(x-x_0\right)+y_0</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> is a point on the line.</p> -->
    <example permid="RHW">
      <statement>
        <p permid="RAS">
          A line passes through <m>(-6,0)</m> and
          <m>(9,-10)\text{.}</m> Find this line's equation in point-slope<!--  and slope-intercept form -->.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="mUB">
        <p permid="dfq">
          We will use the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> to find the slope first.
          After labeling those two points as <m>(\overset{x_1}{-6},\overset{y_1}{0}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{9},\overset{y_2}{-10})\text{,}</m> we have:
          <md permid="SkM">
            <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-0}{9-(-6)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10}{15}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p permid="Jmz">
          Now the point-slope equation looks like <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0\text{.}</m> Next,
          we will use <m>(9,-10)</m> and substitute <m>x_0</m> with <m>9</m> and <m>y_0</m> with <m>-10\text{,}</m> and we have:
          <md permid="yrV">
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)+(-10)</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
<!--
                <p>Next, we will change the point-slope equation into slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+6-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x-4</mrow>
                </md></p> -->
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="arO">
    <title>Standard Form</title>
    <p permid="BmB">
      In <xref ref="section-standard-form">Section</xref>
      we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref> of a linear equation.
      We converted equations from standard form to slope-intercept form and vice versa.
      We also graphed lines from standard form by finding the intercepts of the line.
    </p>
            <!-- <p>A line's equation in standard form looks like <m>Ax+By=C</m>. We need to convert a line's equation from standard form to slope-intercept form, and vice versa.</p> -->
    <example permid="xPf">
      <statement>
        <p permid="xIb">
          <ol label="a." permid="AYg">
            <li permid="hfp">
              <p permid="RWr">
                Convert <m>2x+3y=6</m> into slope-intercept form.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="Nmy">
              <p permid="ydA">
                Convert <m>y=-\frac{4}{7}x-3</m> into standard form.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="TbK">
        <p permid="ptI">
          <ol label="a." permid="oJO">
            <li permid="ttH">
              <p permid="ekJ">
                <md permid="eze">
                  <mrow>2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
                  <mrow>2x+3y\subtractright{2x}\amp=6\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                  <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+6</mrow>
                  <mrow>\divideunder{3y}{3}\amp=\divideunder{-2x+6}{3}</mrow>
                  <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-2x}{3}+\frac{6}{3}</mrow>
                  <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
                </md>
                The line's equation in slope-intercept form is <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="ZAQ">
              <p permid="KrS">
                <md permid="KGn">
                  <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{4}{7}x-3</mrow>
                  <mrow>\multiplyleft{7}y\amp=\multiplyleft{7}(-\frac{4}{7}x-3)</mrow>
                  <mrow>7y\amp=7\cdot(-\frac{4}{7}x)-7\cdot3</mrow>
                  <mrow>7y\amp=-4x-21</mrow>
                  <mrow>7y\addright{4x}\amp=-4x-21\addright{4x}</mrow>
                  <mrow>4x+7y\amp=-21</mrow>
                </md>
                The line's equation in standard form is <m>4x+7y=-21</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p permid="htK">
      To graph a line in standard form,
      we could first change it to slope-intercept form,
      and then graph the line by its <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles.
      A second method is to graph the line by its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.
    </p>

    <example permid="dWo">
      <statement>
        <p permid="dPk">
          Graph <m>2x-3y=-6</m> using its intercepts.
          And then use the intercepts to calculate the line's slope.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="ziT">
        <p permid="VAR">
          We calculate the line's <m>x</m>-intercept by substituting <m>y=0</m> into the equation
          <md permid="qNw">
            <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>2x-3(\substitute{0})\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-3</mrow>
          </md>
          So the line's <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>(-3,0)\text{.}</m>
        </p>

        <p permid="BIa">
          Similarly, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into the equation to calculate the <m>y</m>-intercept:
          <md permid="WUF">
            <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>2(\substitute{0})-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
          </md>
          So the line's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,2)</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="hPj">
          With both intercepts' coordinates, we can graph the line:
        </p>

        <figure permid="udB">
          <caption>Graph of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
          <image width="47%" permid="pId">
            <description>the graph of line 2x-3y=-6 with the x-intercept plotted at (-3,0) and the y-intercept at (0,2).</description>

                <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=2,
                            ymin=-1,ymax=4,
                            minor xtick=,
                            minor ytick=,
                            xtick={-4,-3,...,1},
                            ytick={1,2,3}]
                        \addplot+[domain=-4.5:2]{2/3*x+2};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 2)} node[above left] {$(0,2)$};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 0)} node[above left] {$(-3,0)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p permid="NWs">
          Now that we have graphed the line we can read the slope.
          The rise is 2 units and the run is 3 units so the slope is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="GyX">
    <title>Horizontal, Vertical, Parallel, and Perpendicular Lines</title>
    <p permid="NAT">
      In <xref ref="section-horizontal-vertical-parallel-and-perpendicular-lines">Section</xref>
      we covered what equations of horizontal and vertical lines.
      We also covered the relationships between the slopes of <xref ref="fact-parallel-lines" text="title">parallel</xref>
      and <xref ref="fact-perpendicular-lines" text="title">perpendicular</xref> lines.
    </p>
        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Horizontal, Vertical, Parallel, and Perpendicular Lines</title>

            <p>A horizontal line's equation looks like <m>y=k</m>, while a vertical line's equation looks like <m>x=h</m>. The following figure has graphs of a horizontal line and a vertical line.</p>
        </paragraphs> -->
       <!--  <figure>
            <caption>Graphs of <m>y=3</m> and <m>x=5</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
            <description>a graph with a horizontal line at y=3 and a vertical line at x=5</description>
            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}
                        \addplot[primarycurve]{3} node[pos=0.6,above,align=center] {$y=3$};
                        \addplot[primarycurve,blue] coordinates {(5,-7) (5,7)} node[pos=0.6,left,align=center,blue] {$x=5$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure> -->
        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Parallel and Perpendicular Lines</title>
            <p>Two lines are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.</p> -->
    <example permid="Kdx">
      <statement>
        <p permid="JWt">
          Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>.
          Line <m>n</m> is parallel to <m>m</m>,
          and line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>.
          Find an equation for line <m>n</m> in point-slope form.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="fqc">
        <p permid="akK">
          Since parallel lines have the same slope,
          line <m>n</m>'s slope is also <m>-2</m>.
          Since line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>,
          we can write line <m>n</m>'s equation in point-slope form:
          <md permid="DbO">
            <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
          </md>
            <!-- We can also easily get the line's equation in slope-intercept form:
                <md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-2x+8-3</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-2x+5</mrow>
                </md> -->
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p permid="tIc">
      Two lines are perpendicular if and only if the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.
    </p>

    <example permid="qkG">
      <statement>
        <p permid="qdC">
          Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>.
          Line <m>n</m> is perpendicular to <m>m</m>,
          and line <m>q</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>.
          Find an equation for line <m>q</m> in slope-intercept form.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="Lxl">
        <p permid="GrT">
          Since line <m>m</m> and <m>q</m> are perpendicular,
          the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.
          Because line <m>m</m>'s slope is given as <m>-2</m>,
          we can find line <m>q</m>'s slope is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
        </p>

        <p permid="mzc">
          Since line <m>q</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>,
          we can write line <m>q</m>'s equation in point-slope form:
          <md permid="jiX">
            <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
          </md>
          We can now convert this equation to slope-intercept form:
          <md permid="Pqg">
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-2-3</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-5</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
        <!-- </paragraphs> -->
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="mGg">
    <title>Linear Inequalities in Two Variables</title>
    <p permid="ZPl">
      In <xref ref="section-linear-inequalities-in-two-variables">Section</xref>
      we covered how to graph the solution set for an inequality with two variables as a region in the plane.
    </p>
            <!-- <p>When we graph lines like <m>y=2x+1</m>, we are graphing points which satisfy the relationship <m>y=2x+1</m>, like <m>(0,1), (1,3), (2,5)</m>, etc. Similarly, we can graph linear inequalities like <m>y\gt2x+1</m> by plotting all points which satisfies the inequality, like <m>(0,2), (0,3), (1,4), (1,5)</m>, etc. All these points form a region, instead of a line.</p> -->
    <example permid="WrP">
      <statement>
        <p permid="WkL">
          Graph <m>y\gt2x+1\text{.}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="rEu">
        <p permid="SGl">
          There are two steps to graph an inequality.

          <ol permid="UQX">
            <li permid="FHZ">
              Graph the line <m>y=2x+1\text{.}</m> Because the inequality symbol is <m>\gt\text{,}</m>
              (instead of <m>\ge</m>)
              the line should be dashed
              (instead of solid).
            </li>

            <li permid="lPi">
              Next, we need to decide whether to shade the region above <m>y=2x+1</m> or below it.
              We will choose a point to test whether <m>y\gt2x+1</m> is true.
              As long as the line doesn't cross
              <m>(0,0)\text{,}</m> we will use <m>(0,0)</m> to test,
              because the number <m>0</m> is the easiest number for calculation.
              <md permid="vxp">
                <mrow>y\gt2x+1</mrow>
                <mrow>0\stackrel{?}{\gt}2(0)+1</mrow>
                <mrow>0\stackrel{\text{no}}{\gt}1</mrow>
              </md>
              Because <m>0\gt1</m> is not true,
              the point <m>(0,0)</m> is not a solution and should not be shaded.
              As a result, we shade the region without <m>(0,0)\text{.}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" permid="CyY">
          <figure permid="yNu">
            <caption>Step 1 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
            <image permid="VPm">
              <description>a coordinate plane with y=2x+1 graphed as a dashed line</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                        minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                        xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                        ]
                        \addplot[domain=-3:2,secondarycurve,dashed] {2*x+1};
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>

          <figure permid="eUD">
            <caption>Step 2 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
            <image permid="BWv">
              <description>the previous graph with the region above the line shaded</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                        minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                        xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                        ]
                        \addplot[domain=-3:2,secondarycurve,dashed] {2*x+1};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[above right] {test point: $(0,0)$};
                        \fill[blue, opacity=0.4] (axis cs:-5,-5) -- (axis cs:-3,-5) -- (axis cs:2,5) -- (axis cs:-5,5) -- cycle;
                    \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

